WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:12.000
Hello, I am Alexey Nazimko. I am a marketologist, business coach and consultant in the field of event marketing and personal branding.

00:12.000 --> 00:26.000
I am the author of the book Event Marketing. I teach at the Moscow Business School and I am a teacher of the MBA Communication Management program at the Academy of People's Economy.

00:26.000 --> 00:36.000
Our course, created as part of the MBA Start program of the Moscow Business School, is called Event Marketing. It is dedicated to promoting brands through special events.

00:36.000 --> 00:43.000
A little about the course. The first part of our course is called General Characteristics of Event Marketing.

00:43.000 --> 00:50.000
It will be dedicated to the general parameters of this area, to what is event marketing, what is it different from event management.

00:51.000 --> 00:58.000
We will look at the main types and forms of events, as well as the main principles of the success of special events.

00:58.000 --> 01:04.000
The second part is dedicated to the methods of creativity in event marketing. It consists of two sub-parts.

01:04.000 --> 01:12.000
First, we will get acquainted with the basic methods of creativity, learn to apply them to the development of creative concepts of special events.

01:13.000 --> 01:20.000
The second part of this section will be dedicated to my author's concept of benchmarking for special events.

01:20.000 --> 01:36.000
The third part of the course is called The Types of Events. We will look at the main differences of different types of special events, such as exhibitions, BTL, press conferences, corporate events, sponsorship and charity.

01:36.000 --> 01:41.000
We will learn how to use them with maximum efficiency to promote your brand.

01:41.000 --> 01:49.000
The fourth part of the course is called Events as a Project. We will touch on the managerial side of the matter, not only the marketing one.

01:49.000 --> 02:00.000
We will learn about the project characteristics of a special event, how to set goals correctly, how to look for a contractor and measure the results of the event company's return.

02:00.000 --> 02:20.000
Let's look at the categories related to the concept of event marketing. These are advertising, BTL, PR, training industry, training events, intensive training, entertainment marketing, empirical marketing and neuromarketing.

02:20.000 --> 02:44.000
If we talk about the differences between event marketing and advertising, they are quite fundamental. Advertising is traditionally related to the direct impact on the consumer, and event marketing is based on the interactive forms of interaction between the consumer and the direct contact of the client and the brand.

02:44.000 --> 02:57.000
BTL can be perceived as a narrow field of marketing communications, although, of course, BTL industry specialists claim for something more.

02:57.000 --> 03:18.000
To put it more broadly, BTL industry in Russia is a distribution of free food in gastronomy or sampling. But in a broader sense, BTL can be attributed to any image events, presentations that promote the product.

03:18.000 --> 03:41.000
Recently, it has been said that BTL has come out of the underline, has become a full-fledged technology. This is true. I must say that the spread of the event level in the BTL industry is quite large, from simple sampling, which is difficult to call an event in the full sense of the word, to full-scale advertising.

03:41.000 --> 04:05.000
Public relations also claims to expand its subject area. Communication with the public in the narrow sense of the word can be perceived as a press event, if we talk about the event side of the issue. But, of course, any PR person is engaged in promotion, and in this regard, the work of a PR person is very often limited to the work of a marketer, an advertising specialist and BTL.

04:05.000 --> 04:31.000
The training industry is also part of the event industry recently. But here you need to make certain differences, because, of course, educational events can also be called a corporate event. But it is still an educational event, and it is difficult to compare it in the form of, say, promotional events or corporate parties or presentations.

04:31.000 --> 04:50.000
But if the training acquires some event forms, it becomes spectacular, it is taken out of the training audience somewhere outside, into the fields. If a team is formed, then it can be called a corporate event.

04:50.000 --> 05:16.000
Entertainment marketing, empirical marketing, neuromarketing are rather not a direction of marketing communications, but a certain philosophy of marketing, certain approaches to the impact on the consumer. Entertainment marketing or show marketing, as some Russian marketologists have called it, is designed to either train the consumer or entertain him.

05:17.000 --> 05:30.000
At the same time, entertainment is in the first place. If a company is holding educational seminars to bring consumers to the brand, then this is also done in some form of entertainment.

05:30.000 --> 05:48.000
The concepts of empirical marketing and neuromarketing are close to entertainment, but entertainment marketing often emphasizes the use of art presentation tools for the brand, show, art, for marketing purposes.

05:48.000 --> 06:11.000
Empirical marketing and neuromarketing are more narrow concepts. They imply a general marketing approach that includes the impact on the consumer's feelings. It is difficult to say how different empirical marketing and neuromarketing are, but the main idea is that we are immersed in the space of feelings.

06:12.000 --> 06:30.000
We feel smells, we hear sounds, we experience tactile sensations when in contact with the brand, for example, with a package or with some object. And all this must be used to promote the brand without missing a single channel of impact.

06:30.000 --> 06:46.000
As for the event side of the question, event marketing is often conceptualized through the concept of empirical and neuromarketing, saying that it influences the consumer's feelings and implies direct contact with the consumer and the brand.

06:46.000 --> 07:06.000
An important question is how the concepts of event marketing and event management are defined. Some do not define it, some expand the concept of event marketing. For example, often event marketing is called an industry that promotes brands through special events.

07:06.000 --> 07:35.000
But the traditional limitation is that event marketing implies marketing communication tasks, and event management is only a communication component. Very often when you communicate with professional event managers, you find that event managers who have been working in the industry for many years have not heard the word event marketing, if they did not deal with marketing tasks and if they did not require a marketing justification for the effectiveness of special events.

07:36.000 --> 07:58.000
Events in event marketing. The category of events in event marketing is slightly different from the category of events in the usual word of use. It must be said that there are certain difficulties in translation, because the English event and the Russian event have slightly different meanings.

07:58.000 --> 08:18.000
In Russian, we call the word event historical, epochal. As for the English word, the word event is narrower. The Oxford Dictionary translates it as something happened. Thus, the meaning of this word is fixed, that the event is aimed at some changes.

08:18.000 --> 08:41.000
As for the historical events, there is a separate word in English. In this regard, when we translate event marketing, we increase the degree of significance and scale of these events. In this regard, we can say that the language leads us, and Russian event managers are the creators of the history of the brand woven from the events of special events.

08:41.000 --> 09:01.000
Events in event marketing are such an event that changes the attitude of target audiences and the brand and has subjective significance in their eyes. The issue of the attitude of event marketing to integrated marketing communication is often discussed.

09:01.000 --> 09:25.000
To be honest, I am very careful about the concept of integrated marketing communication, because it often does not give anything specific. Naturally, we must integrate something. Naturally, we must direct our marketing efforts to a single goal of promoting the brand, so that the situation of the swan does not turn out to be a cock and a crane,

09:25.000 --> 09:41.000
when each event and each marketing idea promotes us in different directions. But at the same time, this is a very common position, and moreover, it differs depending on what we integrate with.

09:41.000 --> 10:07.000
So, attentive readers of Kotler remember that there is an internal and external marketing environment of the enterprise, and the approach to integrated marketing communication can imply the integration of this external and internal marketing environment. This means that there is the same brand image for their own and, conditionally speaking, for others, for clients, potential partners, those who are outside and for company employees.

10:07.000 --> 10:31.000
Within the framework of recruiting projects, it has recently become fashionable to combine these two directions. For example, if one of the top managers of a large company meets, say, with students, marketers or other specialists whom the company wants to attract to work, this very often gives a marketing effect.

10:31.000 --> 10:49.000
The same applies to advertising in public places, which contains messages of a recruiting nature. This is also advertising for the brand itself. Thus, some events can integrate internal and external tasks.

10:49.000 --> 11:09.000
In addition, there is an integration of a different kind, that is, the integration of various types of marketing communication, when we try to direct to the same task, say, advertising, communication with the public, special events and so on.

11:19.000 --> 11:39.000
For example, the announcement in the press can imply publicity after the event, direct advertising, online promotion, and so on. In this regard, different types of marketing communication can intersect within one event project.

11:39.000 --> 12:08.000
It is also necessary to remember that the basis of the integration of external and internal marketing environment and various ways of communication in event marketing is the brand platform. Therefore, any event marketer, just a marketer who wants to promote his brand through special events, must first look at the brand platform, and then formulate the goals of the event and look for the funds that will be appropriate and reasonable.

12:09.000 --> 12:24.000
Let's talk about event classification. In fact, there can be as many options as you like, because the more criteria we find in the classification, the more types of events we can select. It all depends on what is significant to us.

12:24.000 --> 12:47.000
But we can name some basic criteria that allow us to distinguish between one type of event and another. Naturally, they will be repeated depending on the criteria. Events can be divided by marketing environment into external and internal. Accordingly, we refer to external events, such as promotional promotions, BTL, advertising campaigns, press conferences, and to internal events, such as corporate events, intensive events, and so on.

12:48.000 --> 13:13.000
There is another way of classification. By type of marketing environment, events can be divided into political, corporate, social, cultural, scientific, sports, and so on. In this case, the difference is made more by the tradition of organizing such events, by the nature of the target audience, and by the tasks, whether they are political, commercial, research, and so on.

13:14.000 --> 13:35.000
Events can be divided by the nature of the participants' interaction into formal and informal. In this case, examples can be absolutely any, because today, in terms of changes in the business culture, many events that used to be thought of as exclusively formal acquire an informal nature.

13:35.000 --> 13:50.000
We already hear calls from progressive marketers to organize shows from press conferences and business exhibitions, although these events used to be extremely formalized.

13:50.000 --> 14:11.000
By the scale of the target audience, we can classify events into international, state, corporate, and micro events. We can refer to international events, such as international summits, international conferences, international level sports competitions, official state holidays, inaugurations, and other government events.

14:12.000 --> 14:34.000
We can refer to corporate events, trainings, presentations, and other events that are most often interesting to event organizers. There are also micro events that we rarely mention, but nevertheless, they take place. These are business meetings, romantic dates, organizations of random coincidences, and raffles.

14:34.000 --> 14:46.000
Raffles have become a trend for private events, and they are also very popular, despite the fact that they are micro events, and usually have a good budget.

14:46.000 --> 15:11.000
According to marketing goals, events can be divided into fixed and achieved ones, and those aimed at changing the situation. If we want to fix the achieved results, we can organize a press conference or a corporate event that summarizes the results of long-term activities, say, within a year or half a year.

15:11.000 --> 15:31.000
As for revolutionary events that are supposed to be radical changes, these are often events that are aimed at rebranding the company, or are associated with crisis communications. Something happened, and we need to somehow react to it, improve the image of the company, and so on.

15:31.000 --> 15:47.000
We can also refer to the presentation of a new product, launching new brands, and so on. We can highlight several general principles of the success of special events. The first principle I called the unity and limitation of time and space.

15:47.000 --> 16:10.000
On the one hand, this is quite obvious, because something is really happening somewhere, we call it an event, a number of people participate in the event, the event has a beginning and an end, but on the other hand, many eventers have already faced this situation when the event ceased to be an event due to the violation of this principle.

16:10.000 --> 16:31.000
Why do we need the unity of time? The fact is that events exist only in the perception of the target audience. As they perceive it, so are the events, and so are their results. Therefore, we need the representatives of the target audience, participants of the event, to experience this event together, to experience it together, and to react to it together.

16:31.000 --> 16:48.000
This is why we gather people together, and this is why we need them to be in common space and in common time. On the other hand, it is necessary that the space is limited. For example, imagine that you decided to hold a corporate party for 60 employees at the stadium.

17:01.000 --> 17:17.000
When this event ends, your audience will simply scatter in this huge space, so some limitation is always necessary. The same applies to time. It is very important that a person perceives that there is a beginning of an event and there is an end to it. Many companies have already faced this.

17:17.000 --> 17:38.000
I want to give an example. For example, in Siberia there is a festival of the alternative theater of Sibaltra. When this brand was launched, it was a festival that lasted about a week and included a lot of performances. But then the owners of this brand decided to commercialize it throughout the year.

17:38.000 --> 18:04.000
As a result, the festival began to fade away, because there was no clearly allocated festival time. The performance was held all year under the brand Sibaltra. In this regard, the event brand fades away and the company turns into a purely promotional one that promotes alternative productions throughout the year. This should be remembered.

18:04.000 --> 18:22.000
The second principle of success of an event is the principle of an attraction. There are different types of attractions. In art theory, this is well worked out. There is an attraction of ugliness, an attraction of disasters, an attraction of beauty. I wrote about this in my book.

18:22.000 --> 18:40.000
But here we need to remember that whatever attraction we arrange for the consumer, we must surprise him with something. If the point of surprise does not come, then the event is not an event, it is just an event for a tick.

18:40.000 --> 18:56.000
For example, when you come to a gastronome and see another sampling, again a promo for a girl, again a stand, again they offer you to try the product. Of course, as an event, you do not perceive it for yourself, it is just an episode. It can't surprise you.

18:56.000 --> 19:16.000
On the other hand, if you see an unusual object, even an unusual growth figure in the same gastronome, then most likely you will be interested in it and you can even tell your friends about it, especially if you manage to involve the organizer of the event in some interaction.

19:16.000 --> 19:31.000
The third principle is called the principle of mutual exchange. This is related to the psychology of the unconscious. The fact is that since ancient times in human society it has developed in such a way that we try to respond to what we have been done.

19:31.000 --> 19:48.000
In general, it is very beneficial to do good to people in this regard, because if you, for example, stretch a person's hand, then assume that he will stretch it in response, otherwise it will be just rudeness. If you greet someone, then assume that they will greet you, and then ask who you are.

19:48.000 --> 20:09.000
The same applies to special events. If you organize a good vacation for employees, or organize a good show for consumers, or engage in free training for consumers, presenting a new variety of computer technology, then usually you are paid for good.

20:09.000 --> 20:35.000
Of course, there is no such strict rule that if, for example, a journalist came to a press event, he must make a publication. Moreover, the quality of the brochure does not always affect the publication activity. Nevertheless, if you organized something really interesting that your target audience liked, the chances of getting monetary return from this are greatly increased.

20:35.000 --> 20:52.000
The fourth principle is the principle of ritualistic action. This is also a psychological factor of special events. The fact is that there is a festive stereotype. What is a holiday for the mass audience?

20:52.000 --> 21:12.000
It is a disco, a performance of artists, a banquet, and so on. When we start organizing corporate events, we face a contradiction. The audience is waiting for one thing, and we need to surprise it and come up with something else.

21:12.000 --> 21:32.000
In this regard, in order to create a truly interesting special event, you need to observe the balance of social rituals that are practiced, say, in the event of a business conference or a corporate holiday, and what you can offer your audience.

21:32.000 --> 21:51.000
If you completely go into the ritual scheme, the event will cease to be an event and become an event for a tick. If you find something new, it is important not to get carried away, because by destroying social conventions, you can get out of the space of attention and interaction with your target audience.

21:51.000 --> 22:15.000
The fifth principle is the principle of subjectivity. Events always exist in the consciousness of target audiences, as does the brand. This makes the concept of event marketing absolutely marketing and branding. If the event is perceived as significant to the target audience, then you can say that you have achieved what you wanted and the event is organized.

22:15.000 --> 22:35.000
If this does not happen, then we have a regular event. We must always remember that in addition to the direct reaction of target audiences, this reaction can be designed in the future, when the event is already completed, and thus prolong the communication effect of the event.

22:35.000 --> 22:56.000
What do I mean? Let's say people came to the event, they didn't like something there, and they had a negative impression of the event about the brand. Some time passes, and the details of what caused the negative are forgotten, and here comes the usual PR.

22:56.000 --> 23:15.000
For example, you post good reviews of some participants of the event on the website, or you post information about the success stories associated with a particular event on a corporate website or in a corporate newspaper.

23:15.000 --> 23:31.000
Seeing that there is a general idea of ​​a positive event, some representatives of the target audience, skeptical, begin to change their opinion, they begin to think, maybe something was really good, and so on.

23:31.000 --> 23:55.000
Of course, the event should be high-quality, it should be planned so as not to cause a negative impression to the audience, but we must always remember that public opinion can also be designed, and events are not just some actions within the event, but all the space of perception of the brand and the event that exists outside the event when it is already completed.

23:56.000 --> 24:21.000
The sixth principle of success is called the principle of dramatization. I think that event managers should learn from directors of theatrical productions, directors of films, writers, because any work of art has its heroes, has some development, has a climax, has a culmination, and has an effective ending.

24:22.000 --> 24:47.000
The same characteristics should be used for a successful marketing event. Why is this necessary? Very often, the concept of an event in words is formulated. On the one hand, this is very difficult from the point of view of selling the event as a marketing tool, and on the other hand, it is difficult from the point of view of selling the event directly to its participants,

24:48.000 --> 25:00.000
because the participant reads the announcements of the event, then he reads reports about the event, and he wants to be formulated in words, what was there, what happened, what was in the event so unusual.

25:01.000 --> 25:17.000
If we think in terms of visual images, in the principle of making us beautiful, then we represent the picture of the event. This is very good, because then photos from the event can be posted on blogs, on websites, in newspapers, and the information effect can be prolonged in this way.

25:17.000 --> 25:31.000
But the picture is always static, and in this regard, visual images are not self-sufficient for us. We can come up with an interesting design of the event, we can hold the event in an unusual place, and this is not bad in itself.

25:31.000 --> 25:44.000
But if there is no internal dynamics, if there is no story that the participants of the event live through, then in the end we will simply have nothing to say about what happened.

25:45.000 --> 26:01.000
The principle of dramatization is also important for communication with the press, because in addition to the visual image, the journalist needs to predict something about the event, something that happened there, something that made some changes.

26:01.000 --> 26:16.000
In this regard, it is very important at the stage of planning the event to see its dynamics, its structural units, its composition, almost in the artistic sense, including the literary work, and to be able to formulate the concept of the event in words.

26:16.000 --> 26:36.000
We move on to practical questions from the general understanding of the strategy of event marketing. We move on to the question of how to create the concept of special events and at the same time make them creative.

26:36.000 --> 26:51.000
There are certain difficulties in the event industry, despite the fact that it grows by almost 25% every year, and there are more good events that can be told and written about.

26:51.000 --> 27:05.000
This is due to several reasons, which cause a fairly low level of creativity in special events. First, this is the complexity of the organizational part of the event.

27:05.000 --> 27:28.000
Years pass before the event manager goes from the task of organizing events to creative tasks. Especially when it comes to mass events, they include a lot of structural elements and it is quite difficult to coordinate internal logistics and events.

27:29.000 --> 27:44.000
Now the event industry is at the stage when we already have good technology for organizing events and good event managers, and therefore we begin to think about how to make events truly interesting.

27:44.000 --> 27:59.000
The second factor that affects the low level of creativity in the event industry is the ritualistic nature of the holiday. This is the holiday stereotype that I have already mentioned.

27:59.000 --> 28:16.000
If there is a certain horizon of expectations from the target audience, then very often the organizers and organizers of special events simply go along the usual path of satisfying these needs and justifying these expectations.

28:16.000 --> 28:24.000
Although in fact, you need to come up with something else to surprise the target audience, and this is what creative technology is for.

28:25.000 --> 28:42.000
Another factor that reduces the level of creativity in events is low budgets. This thesis is quite controversial, because on the one hand, the limitation of budgets often makes you give up on many interesting ideas.

28:42.000 --> 28:58.000
On the other hand, the limitation of resources is a trigger that triggers creativity mechanisms, makes company representatives and event agents come up with something really interesting.

28:58.000 --> 29:26.000
This is often called KVN marketing, when creativity outweighs the budget of events. Indeed, we can look at the events produced by different companies and find that large corporations arrange rather trivial events, while small and medium-sized businesses are alluring and create interesting creative concepts.

29:26.000 --> 29:39.000
This is why funky marketing and funky business are often primarily related to the post-industrial segment and primarily to small and medium-sized businesses.

29:39.000 --> 29:59.000
Another factor that certainly affects the reduction of the level of creativity in events is that in any advertising agency there are already proven and worked out creative methods that are used to train employees, to come to work, to train advertisers.

29:59.000 --> 30:14.000
But no one is preparing event managers, so they have to come up with these creative ideas on their own, without using special technologies. We already have them, and we will learn this during our course.

30:14.000 --> 30:31.000
It is also important to note that the event itself assumes creativity, it separates it from the event, because it is creativity that creates the ability to surprise its target audience and make the event truly significant in their eyes.

30:31.000 --> 30:59.000
There are quite a few creative methods, and the use of certain technologies depends on a specific person, on his or her personal preferences. Therefore, it is necessary to test various ways of generating creative ideas during training and choose what is most convenient for everyone. But without trying, we cannot find out about it. So, let's go!

30:59.000 --> 31:21.000
Now we will consider a training case where we will train and develop creative ideas. This is the brand of Caterpillar clothes and shoes. Many of you know that Caterpillar produces working equipment, but in addition they have a promo brand and a separate direction of Caterpillar activities.

31:21.000 --> 31:48.000
Caterpillar is a working clothing brand. If we describe the platform of this brand, we can say that it focuses on anti-glamour, utility and work aesthetics. These clothes and shoes have long gone beyond the framework of the purely work sphere, they are worn in everyday wear, and therefore the brand needs to expand its client base.

31:48.000 --> 32:14.000
In addition to accessories and clothing items that exist constantly in collections, there are also seasonal collections that require promotion. The shows of the new Caterpillar collections and the presentation of these new collections will be the task on which we will work on our creative technologies within the framework of our training.

32:15.000 --> 32:36.000
The first and perhaps one of the most common creative methods is brainstorming. Almost everyone has heard about it and almost everyone knows its basic rules. Just in case, we will repeat them. During a brainstorming, the versions are not criticized, they are only expressed, and only then discussed.

32:36.000 --> 32:45.000
The time in the framework of a brainstorming is limited, and it is necessary to create as many creative ideas as possible within it.

32:46.000 --> 33:06.000
The third rule of a brainstorming is that the criticism of all ideas is carried beyond the framework of the brainstorming itself and is carried out later. There are different types of brainstorming. Sometimes ideas are simply expressed verbally, and someone fixes them, and then there is a discussion.

33:07.000 --> 33:28.000
But if you experience some organizational difficulties, if the members of the design group are inclined to interrupt each other and still proceed to discuss ideas, or feel some kind of uncertainty, then you can conduct a silent brainstorming, simply writing down your versions on pieces of paper and then only voicing them during the discussion.

33:29.000 --> 33:43.000
We move on to the first task. We will need to come up with at least five ideas for the presentation of the new collection of the Caterpillar clothing brand. The recommended time for completing the task is 10 minutes.

33:55.000 --> 34:03.000
I congratulate you on your successful completion of the task 1. I think you all have done it.

34:03.000 --> 34:07.000
Let's see what answers could be given.

34:07.000 --> 34:12.000
The answers that I and my trainees offer.

34:12.000 --> 34:21.000
For example, you can attach the presentation of the Caterpillar brand to the day of spring labor, to May 1.

34:22.000 --> 34:32.000
Another version suggests that you can give a stamp with a boot print of Caterpillar to the best partners who have left their mark on the history of the brand's development.

34:32.000 --> 34:37.000
Another creative idea involves a presentation in the planetarium.

34:37.000 --> 34:42.000
The future, which remains in the lives of earthlings, is recognized only by Caterpillar.

34:42.000 --> 34:47.000
This is such a futurological concept of event promotion of this brand.

34:48.000 --> 34:55.000
You can hold a presentation in a sandy quarry and pour champagne to guests using Caterpillar's work equipment.

34:55.000 --> 35:00.000
This allows you to integrate the presentation of the brand's clothes and work equipment.

35:00.000 --> 35:04.000
It is a reminder of the company's main specialization.

35:04.000 --> 35:13.000
You can also hold a show of a new collection, which will be presented by the best workers, farmers of Moscow and Moscow region.

35:13.000 --> 35:23.000
Thus, the company becomes the core of its target audience and can promote the work equipment and clothing brand at the same time.

35:23.000 --> 35:27.000
Any creative technology has advantages and disadvantages.

35:27.000 --> 35:29.000
The brainstorming is no exception.

35:29.000 --> 35:35.000
The advantage of the brainstorming is that it allows you to organize the process of generating ideas.

35:36.000 --> 35:46.000
Often, in an authoritarian leadership, conditions are created for employees to express their ideas, and not just follow their leaders.

35:46.000 --> 35:49.000
This is also one of the advantages of the brainstorming.

35:49.000 --> 35:56.000
At the same time, the brainstorming is not self-sufficient, because in its process we only record ideas,

35:56.000 --> 36:02.000
but we have no idea what is happening in the space of the skull of the participants in the discussion.

36:02.000 --> 36:11.000
The brainstorming creates some basic prerequisites for the creation of an idea, but does not affect the creative strategy of the participants.

36:11.000 --> 36:15.000
We move on to the creative technology 6 hats by De Bono.

36:15.000 --> 36:18.000
It is also well known.

36:18.000 --> 36:24.000
Sometimes, the participants of the creative group really wear colored hats.

36:24.000 --> 36:26.000
Sometimes they are just given roles.

36:26.000 --> 36:31.000
The role of the white hat is to analyze the numbers and facts without passion.

36:31.000 --> 36:35.000
The role of the black hat is to express negative judgments.

36:35.000 --> 36:41.000
The yellow hat, on the contrary, expresses only positive judgments about any idea or concept.

36:41.000 --> 36:47.000
The green hat is the role of the supposed creative beginning, expressing creative ideas.

36:47.000 --> 36:52.000
The red hat expresses emotional reactions, and the blue one summarizes the results.

36:52.000 --> 36:54.000
Task 2.

36:54.000 --> 37:01.000
During the brainstorming, we received an offer to make a show of the new collection of caterpillars in a space style.

37:01.000 --> 37:05.000
In the future, space colonists will recognize only the caterpillar.

37:05.000 --> 37:09.000
Refer to this idea from the position of each of the 6 hats.

37:09.000 --> 37:13.000
The recommended time for completing the task is 10 minutes.

37:23.000 --> 37:25.000
